context: <b5_0><b8_0>Tajikistan<b8_0/><b5_0/> (i/tɑːˈdʒiːkᵻstɑːn/, /təˈdʒiːkᵻstæn/, or /tæˈdʒiːkiːstæn/; Persian: تاجيكستان‎‎ Тоҷикистон [tɔd͡ʒikɪsˈtɔn]), officially the Republic of Tajikistan (Persian: جمهورى تاجيكستان‎‎ Tajik: Ҷумҳурии Тоҷикистон, Çumhuriji Toçikiston/Jumhuriyi Tojikiston; Russian: Респу́блика Таджикистан, Respublika Tadzhikistan), is a mountainous, landlocked country <a0_0>in Central Asia<a0_0/> with an estimated <a1_0>8 million people<a1_0/> in <b6_0>2013<b6_0/>, and an <a2_0>area of 143,100 km2 (<b9_0>55,300<b9_0/> sq mi)<a2_0/>. It is bordered by Afghanistan to the south, Uzbekistan to the west, Kyrgyzstan to the north, and <a3_0>China<a3_0/> to the east. Pakistan lies to the south, separated by the narrow <a4_0>Wakhan Corridor<a4_0/>. Traditional homelands of Tajik people included <b7_0>present-day Tajikistan, Afghanistan and Uzbekistan<b7_0/>.
